<DOC><DOCNO> AP891204-0036 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-04-89 0408EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WomenLawyers     12-04 0245</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Women Lawyers,0251</SECOND><HEAD>Survey Finds Sexual Harassment in Large U.S. Law Firms</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sexual harassment and limited opportunity foradvancement are part of a woman's work environment at large U.S.law firms, a study says.   The survey, published in today's edition of the National LawJournal, was based on responses from 918 women lawyers who work inlarge law firms in 13 cities.   Most women said they were at a disadvantage when it came toadvancement. Sixty-four percent said men had a better chance atgaining management positions and 49 percent said men were morelikely to be promoted.   According to the survey, 60 percent of respondents said they hadexperienced unwanted sexual attention, such as sexual teasing,remarks or questions, from co-workers or clients. Nearly one-thirdsaid they had experienced sexual looks or gestures.   The lawyers who responded to the survey earned between $50,000and $250,000 a year. Thirteen percent said they felt their malecounterparts earned higher salaries and bigger bonuses.   The majority of the women felt they had to give up time forfamily, friends or outside interests to pursue their law careers,but they indicated that male lawyers made the same sacrifices.   The survey participants worked in Atlanta, Boston, Chicago,Cleveland, Dallas, Houston, Los Angeles, Miami, Philadelphia, NewYork, San Francisco, Tampa and Washington, D.C.   The survey was conducted by the National Law Journal and WestPublishing of Minneapolis, Minn., the nation's largest publisher oflegal publications.</TEXT></DOC>